WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:00.310 --> 00:00:08.080
A country torn to pieces. A people divided
into groups, forced to fight their own brothers.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:16.040
Lives caught in between the claws of two great
ideological enemies. And an army in retreat,

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:18.710
as another advances.

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:25.970
Army Group North becomes trapped in the Courland
Pocket in Latvia. People say that the trap

00:00:25.970 --> 00:00:32.450
could have been avoided. People say they should
have evacuated them. And people say that Hitler

00:00:32.450 --> 00:00:38.800
is to blame - it was his ‘fortress’ and
‘stand fast’ mentalities that resulted

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:46.290
in the waste of an entire army group in Courland.
His generals call him ‘mad’ for ordering

00:00:46.290 --> 00:00:53.050
his men to stand fast and fight to the death
when he has so little manpower. And Courland

00:00:53.050 --> 00:01:01.370
- a siege larger than that of Stalingrad - is
a great example of this. Or is it?

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:08.140
How did Army Group North become trapped? Was
this avoidable? Why didn’t they evacuate

00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:15.049
them? Who is to blame for this? And why didn’t
the Soviets destroy the pocket? Were they

00:01:15.049 --> 00:01:21.110
capable of destroying the pocket? Did they
try to? In this series, we will attempt to

00:01:21.110 --> 00:01:28.930
answer all these questions. Filthy detailed.
Super accurate. History. This is BATTLESTORM,

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:33.840
the story for the Courland Pocket 1944 to
45.

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:46.679
In this video series we will look at the Soviet
offensives of 1944 that resulted in the Courland

00:01:46.679 --> 00:01:56.060
Pocket, and the six battles in Courland that
took place from October 1944 to May 1945.

